				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Changes made to AE nerf<a name="61009"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Sep 8 04 1:23 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote"> Of all the classes in EQ, bards are definitely the red-headed
<br />
step child that they just seem to love to beat down
<br />
constantly. Just off the top of my head let's see how many
<br />
nerfs I can think of. </span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
I'm going to play some devil's advocate so don't take this the wrong way....
<br />
 
<br />
One of the reasons they justified this nerf is because they felt that the use of AE songs to kite hoards of mobs was not only unbalancing, but was not working as intended. Same principle applies to EN as well. Bards don't work like most classes, there has been a lot of talk about this in the past and I'm surprised it's not coming up in this thread. You're not comparing apples to apples when you talk about bards and casters soloing content, risk vs reward, down time etc. What if a lot of the abilities we take for granted were never intended to be used the way we use them? How can a nerf to something like that not be justified? It then becomes a foggy gray area of opinions and half truths, you can justify anything you want in life, just rationalize and bs, most of us do it on a fairly regular basis, h*ll a lot of us get paid good money to do it. We can't tell if something is &quot;working as intended&quot; or not, but I can say for sure that we have abilities no other classes have, mostly due to expirimental folks out there pushing the envelope of class defenition and being creative. Gives someone a toothpick and enough training and they can make it a leathal weapon, whether a toothpick was intended to be used like that or not. 
<br />
This can be argued back and forth forever, and while I agree with the nerf in *some* respects I disagree on a lot of things too and I can't deny that I feel a bit miffed at getting the bat. I'm going to keep playing and I'm going to keep finding better ways to be a bard because that's what I love doing. 
<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
